passages.text: Up to Neutral as Risk/Reward More Balanced; TP Maintained

With Talabat's shares down \(20\%\) in the last 3 months, underperforming DFMGI by 30pp (u/p by \(\sim 50\) pp since IPO in Dec- 24), we see current valuations fairly reflecting a more competitive environment. The key catalysts flagged in our initiation have largely played out: we saw Keeta's expansion to Talabat's markets (Qatar launched, UAE/Kuwait likely coming soon); Talabat started to revise its margin guidance after 2Q25 (FY25 guidance implies \(\sim 0.5\) pp margin decline in 2H25 vs. 1H25); the market is now pricing \(\sim 4.5 - 5\%\) LT EBITDA/GMV margin, in line with our expectations. Our estimates and AED1.2 TP are unchanged, now implying a positive TSR, hence we upgrade the stock to Neutral. We also provide key takeaways from Meituan's 2Q25 profit warning and DHER's 2Q25 results.

Valuations more reasonable; Market assumes similar LT margin as us - - Talabat is now trading on \(\sim 16.4x / 16.3x\) 2025/26e P/E, consistent with our valuation target set in the Initiation report and at a discount to peers (26x/19x in 2025/26e). Moreover, Talabat trades at a discount to the regional peer Jahez (see our recent downgrade to Sell), despite Talabat's stronger scale and market positions. We estimate the market is now pricing \(\sim 4.5 - 5\%\) LT EBITDA/GMV margin, in line with our expectations.

Meituan's Keeta in Focus - - On Aug 19, Keeta entered the first Talabat's market, Qatar, with the similar value proposition as in KSA: promotions, vouchers, unlimited free delivery for all, on- time delivery promise. We expect launching in other Talabat's markets, particularly Kuwait and UAE, in the coming months. While Meituan maintained its positive view on Keeta's international expansion targets (reaching RMB100bn GMV by 2033), 2Q25 profit warning due higher domestic competition (see Alicia Yap's downgrade) could be viewed as incrementally positive for Talabat given potentially lower spend on aggressive expansion by Keeta.

What can change our view? - - In order to turn more positive, we would need to see (1) street estimates bottoming out (we are \(11\%\) below BBG on 2026e EBITDA). (2) Meituan showing signs of slower MENA expansion (not the case at the moment despite higher competition in mainland China). (3) Limited churn of high value customers and maintaining vendor- funded (rather than shifting to platform- funded) promotions. With Talabat's shares down c.20% in the last 3 months, underperforming DFMGI by 30pp (u/p by - 50pp since IPO in Dec- 24), Talabat is now trading on - 16x 25/26e P/E, consistent with our valuation target set in the Initiation report and a discount to peers median (26x/19x in 2025/26e).

Moreover, at current price, based on our DCF and assuming 11.5- 12% WACC, we think the market is pricing 4.5- 5% LT EBITDA margin, a material decline vs. current levels (- 6.5%) and in line with our LT assumption (5%).

Essentially, the key catalyst that we flagged in our initiation have played out: (1) We saw Keeta's expansion to Talabat's markets (Qatar launched, UAE/Kuwait pending), (2) Talabat started to revise its margin guidance post 2Q25 (FY25 guidance implies - 0.5pp margin decline in 2H25 vs. 1H25), (3) market started to price a more significant margin pressure (in line with our expectations), also likely affected by Jahez 2Q25 miss amidst Keeta's expansion.

Alicia Yap downgraded Meituan following 2Q25 profit warning due to higher competition in core delivery segment - Meituan (3690. HK) - Uncertainty on When CLC Could Regain Profitability; DG to Neutral

Regarding the internal expansion, mgmt. reiterated their target to achieve RMB10Obn (\\~USD14bn) of international GMV by 2033, although emphasizing the fierce competition in Brazil and a careful, patient approach to market entry.

Meituan didn't comment on further expansion plans in MENA, although for now we think it is on track considering recent launch in Qatar, a number of job postings and Keeta's official Linkedln post (as of Aug 25, 2025) flagging partnership with a UAE manpower provider as Keeta "...gears up for UAE launch". For now, we continue to anticipate Keeta's launch in other Talabat's markets, particularly Kuwait and UAE, at the coming months (2025- end/early 2026).

Note that our analysts still expect material operating losses from Meituan's new initiatives, including Keeta: RMB9.1bn/7.4bn (USD1.3bn/1bn) in 2025/26e, not indicating of international program slowing its expansion.

We realize that higher domestic losses by Meituan could be viewed by investors incrementally positive for Talabat given potentially lower spend on aggressive intentional expansion by Keeta (not our base case currently), particularly in case of further domestic deterioration. At the same time, Meituan's profit warning could
also indicate how quickly a leading platform's margin can deteriorate in a case of price wars between well- funded players keen to grab market share.

Keeta's first MENA market was Saudi Arabia, currently dominated by HungerStation, while Talabat has somewhat similar leading positions in MENA markets outside of Saudi. We look for any read- across in KSA as an indication of what could happen in the markets where Talabat operates after Keeta enters.

DHER's KSA order volumes remained at \(>20\%\) in 2Q25, a slight acceleration vs. 1Q25 as per mgmt., though 1Q was negatively affected by Ramadan shift. DHER flagged enhanced subscription offerings and vendor- funded promotions, as well as indicated growth investments in the country ("low double digit investments", in EUR mn as we understand).
We note that Jahez saw volumes improving in KSA to \(+14\%\) in 2Q25 vs. \(+7\%\) in 1Q, although at the cost of higher investments with KSA EBITDA dropping by \(37\%\) YoY.

LT EBITDA margin sustained at \(\sim 6 - 6.5\%\) , similar to 2025e WACC at 10.5- 11%
EBITDA margin moves to \(\sim 5\%\) after 2027 WACC at 11.5%
Higher level of investments: EBITDA margins decline to \(\sim 3 - 3.5\%\) WACC at 12%

Talabat has leading positions in the food delivery market in the countries of operation (UAE, Kuwait, Egypt, Iraq, Qatar, Bahrain, Oman, Jordan) with market shares (GMV) \(2x - 10x\) above #2 player as per the company, confirmed by our traffic data trends, as well as by proprietary consumer survey. Talabat reached USD7.4bn and \(>6.5mn\) MAU in 2024 ( \(\sim 6.5x\) orders per month per active customer). Adj. EBITDA/GMV margin was \(6.7\%\) in 2024, above all regional and global delivery peers.

We rate Talabat Neutral. Following recent under- performance we believe the valuation now more fairly captures risks to Talabat's industry- leading margin in an increasingly competitive landscape. After the launch in Qatar, we expect Meituan to expand into UAE and Kuwait (currently dominated by Talabat) at the end of 2025, applying the same aggressive playbook as in its recent effective launch in Saudi Arabia. Higher competition will likely constrain Talabat's margins, which we think are close to their peaks, however, we think it is reflected in the current price (market- implied margin is close to our expectations).

Our target price for Talabat is AED1.2 and is based on 50/50 mix of (1) DCF: WACC \(11.5\%\) (10% GCC/15% non GCC), terminal growth rate \(3\%\) , and long- term EBITDA/GMV margin at \(5\%\) (- 1.7pp below 2024); (2) Target 2026e P/E of \(16x\) (20% discount to peer median).

Key upside risks to our TP include:  Later- than- expected launch / Higher TAM growth from Meituan launch.  Limited churn on high value customers.  Company specific initiatives (e.g. AdTech, higher efficiency and cost cutting)  Regulation changes  Maintaining vendor- funded (rather than shifting to platform- funded)  promotions  Buybacks
The key downside risks to our TP include:  Higher than expected levels of investments leading to EBITDA margin  dropping below 5% longer- term (our base case)  Macro risks  Overhang risks  Regulation
